@node "introduÁ„o" "Introduction"

   AIP is a program for using the Amiga as ISP, people call your phone
line(s) so AIP will answer this, proceed with login and connect to Internet
(or your internal TCP-IP network).

   Much like any other Un*xoid Internet Access provider! In fact, AIP was
written aiming this.

   You can also run a BBS (with freeware Max's BBS software and proper
patching for shared-access serial)


   This software runs well on very simple hardware, AIP was successfully
used in an A500+A590 2,5 Mb fast and softkicked KS 2.04 running also a WWW
server.


   AIP maintain userlist and userlevel-access files so it will, if defined:

   - limit user by time/connection

   - lock/enable an entire userlevel

   (and that's all, all other limits claimed in 'conf' are not implemented)


   AIP also, theorically, supports multinode BUT:

   - file-sharing routines are not ready (1% done, pffsss..)
     because this the multinode code (which works!) is currently useless.
:(

   - you have to compile different versions for using different config
files, it means you'll have to maintain independent userlists, unless you
write the file-sharing missing code.


   BBS support is NOT multinode (at least using Max's BBS with that patch).

 ------------------------

   * WARNING *

   This is an incomplete software, no longer being developed by the author.
   The source is included, further additions to this program is YOUR
responsability.

   The sources have comments in portuguese language, perhaps i'll translate
that in future. Sorry.
@endnode

@node "usandoAIP" "Using AIP"

 @{b}1. @{ub}Install the following files:

    conf, lixo, lixo2, semaforo to DH1: (the root of DH1)

    AmigaInetProvider where you want.

 @{b}2. @{ub}Edit the following files according yout taste:

    conf     - serial.device, userlevels configuration.
    lixo     - the userlist, with login/passwords, etc.
    lixo2    - userlist _backup_, it's always overwritten.
    semaforo - semaphore, currently this one is useless.

 @{b}3.@{ub} Install the PPP SANA-II driver (sug.: the Holger Kruse's in Aminet)
    and look at 'Inicia PPP0' and 'Encerra PPP0' files i made.
    @{b}Remember to set this PPP to use serial.device as SHARED!!!@{ub}

 @{b}4.@{ub} Install Max's BBS and MAXsTD (in case you want to have BBS too)

 @{b}5.@{ub} Start AmigaInetProvider (note that the program CANNOT be stopped once
    started)


  basically is this.. but i may have forgotten something.
@endnode

@node "histÛria" "Some history"

   AIP started being developed in 4th semester of 1996, when i and a friend
of mine started to create a firm for providing Internet services (among
them, the access itself). He entered with some hardware and business
experience, i entered with the programming.

   In that time i had just RKM 1.3 and 68000 books and i knew how to program
in Pascal, but no programming experience with Amiga.

   So everything was very hard since Amiga OS was a completely new thing for
me, i had to learn it while programming (so you can see how strange the code
of AIP is).


   But things weren't easy, Brazil was in crisis (as always...) and we had
no concrete interested clients.

   In march/1997, after i made a 2 weeks long trip, that friend of mine, my
business pal, came to me and told me that there was no perspective of
business (we needed a minimum of clients for helping the system up while the
first months).

   Said this and went for his life, taking the equipments he came with
months before. I chose some things we bought because i had to stay with
something, it was my money too, lost money.


   All the hard work while developing our softwares and network was lost,
and i had no way to recover the lost time. So recently i decided to make
part of it, AIP, freely available... Perhaps there's someone who will find
it useful.



   So there's a lesson: don't invest too much in something if you're
depending on someone else too.

   And don't mix idiotic friends with serious business.

@endnode

